			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>In that other game, XoX, there is still quite a gap between hardcore raiders and casuals. BUT it has not been expanded sufficiently nor have things like level and AA yard markers been moved far enough so the gap between the Can't/Wont's and the Can Do's is all that readily apparent.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Still, my youngest son is geared so much better than any casual player it's almost a problem. Not mind you because raiders/casuals do the same group and solo content&nbsp;- its' because there is a PvP aspect to the game where tremendously better equipment matters.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think before making such sweeping statements as 4 million can't be wrong you should be aware of what the factors really are:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>1. Nobody want's to join a game as a n00bie that contains players that have benefitted from 5+ years of advancement. Especially if there is not a substantial population of new players to enjoy the game with you.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2. Nobody wants to stay in a game where years of&nbsp;<U>failure</U> to advance has put them years behind. "I can't succeed at EQ, maybe there's a <U>new</U> game where that's not so apparent."</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Don't point the finger at Developer for not making content in which casual players can advance. They have. But if 5% of the player population&nbsp;rises to the top, it's also true X% settle to the bottom.Should SoE examine player data and decide if you suck sufficiently and might move to a new game they'll wave a magic wand and you won't suck so bad??</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>3. When looking to buy a game, the tendancy is to buy the newer one in a genre. The list of EQ "killers" is fairly long, yet a dozen of them never made it to the market, never broke 1 million subscribers, and/or have closed their doors and turned out the lights.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think there are some good ideas in XoX, don't get me wrong. But horrible cartoony graphics,&nbsp;very little end game content and not much of an indication that they are going to address the issue has been causing quite a number of my acquintances to return to EQ despite the fact that they have "lost" a year of advancement.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>IMO it's more likely that a XoX killer will emerge in the next year or two than a genuine EQ killier. XoX has almost 0 to offer except that it is not EQ. A whole bunch of games who's main selling point was that they are "not EQ" no longer exist.</DIV><p>Message Edited by Battleblade-Xegony on <span class=date_text>10-24-2005</span> <span class=time_text>02:03 PM</span>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
