			>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>A whole bunch of games who's main selling point was that they are "not EQ" no longer exist.</DIV>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>The most fun part is that they often advertise based on the premise that they're "not EQ"... I vividly remember reading on the Dark Age of Camelot website that they would "never nerf a character" like some other online games... that is until they realized that they too couldn't come out with a perfectly balanced character system.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>While a lot of games come out with the premise that they're "not EQ"...&nbsp;some players come back because of two reasons..</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>A)&nbsp; The game turns out to be too similar to EQ, and would rather have familiar EQ bugs than new ones.&nbsp; Kinda like getting used to&nbsp;Vito's local pizza place that burns the crust, and then switching to the gourmet pizza that tastes the same, but the sauce is too acidic... bah... lets go back to Vito's.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>B)&nbsp; They realize that while they thought they wanted something that was "not EQ"... but either really DO want EQ, or at least would rather have EQ than whatever it was that promoted it wasn't EQ.&nbsp; Kinda like becoming sick of eating Vito's Pizza all day, and going to&nbsp;Joe's new buffet place.&nbsp; Once you realize&nbsp;Joe's buffet place is stocked full of&nbsp;crud w/ dirty serving spoons... you realize... even though&nbsp;you're sick of Pizza... you'd rather have that than go back to Joe's.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Either way... I feel like some Pizza now... </DIV>
