			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 314 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>"My main point is, with the gap expanding like it is, people who are friends in two different levels of progress in the game will find it difficult to play together as their characters, and that sholdn't happen.&nbsp;"</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This is the concern I've been trying to express as well. I don't wish to deny raiders or even more hardcore non-raiders the benefits of their hard work on gaining gear and AAs. So it's not so much an issue of fairness, as a practical matter of how do friends that have different playstyles both enjoy spending time together in game for those few hours a week that their schedules mesh?</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I do have a friend who is currently in my servers top raiding guild. Nothing I can tank would be even the slightest challenge for a group at his progression, nothing that drops would be at all useful to him, and he'd get substantially better xp soloing than grouping with us anyway. Conversely, anything that would be a challenge for him, would drop items he'd find useful, satisfy any kind of progression he's working on, or would gain him what he would consider 'decent' xp is going to be far beyond anything I could handle in my primary role. I become relegated to gimp status being nothing more than a tiny amount of extra dps. (And it is tiny. With very few offensive AA's and weapons only slightly better than the droga combo, a mage pet can out-dps me, I've parsed it.)</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This is the gap that has been steadily increasing. It's not just a matter of numbers on items, but in how different playstyles interact with each other. In the early days of the game it was not unusual to see&nbsp;raiders and casuals grouping together in the same content, both there for something they&nbsp;felt was worth the effort. But the amount of content raiders and casuals can share in that manner has dwindled dramatically. When a casual player and a raider get together now, the vast majority of content will have either the raider getting&nbsp;much less xp than he's used to and passing on anything that drops, or the casual player is gimped into content he's truly not geared for.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>10-27-2005</span> <span class=time_text>10:57 AM</span>
		</span>
