	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=80701'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#CC6600;'>JazzyJoyce</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Master<br>
			
				Posts: 719<br>
				
				Registered: 11-17-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=80701'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=12205#M12205">72</a> of 332
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 244 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Trying to fight the urge, but I can't help it. I'm going to the original topic of this thread, and I'm going to play devil's advocate, and see what happens.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If there was group-able content, that enable'd casual's to get drops that were compatible to top gear, then there should be GROUP Content, that demands this gear... I don't think anyone would dissagree with that. By compatible, I mean compatible, not equal, but with enough effort and skill, one could be able to compete and a better player would be noticeable as a better player, not just for the gear they wear. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The biggest argument I see coming over this topic (Biggest, not the only one), is there is no need for it. I say, make there be a need for it then, make content that this gear is needed in, and this gear drops in. Groupable content, that takes this kind of resist, Hp/Ac, etc. This would end that part of the debate, but then would bring the one that is more important in my opinion, and also in&nbsp; my opinion, the only reason one really argue's it.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If this content existed, and the drops were there, then it might make raiding trivialized, in that you will still need the gear, but don't have to raid to get it. You could group for the gear, but still have to raid to progress through certain content, but not through class progression. In other words, if this content existed, one could group through it, and progress their toon to the maximum, but not the content itself (allow'd to play in it, so to speak). The hardest part of raiding, is getting the people to work together as a team, gearing up really shouldn't be the biggest amount of time spent on raiding. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This game has two options, and both should lead to the same destiny, the raider should be able to get their first, but shouldn't be the only way to progress a character to the maximum. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I might not actually be making the point I'm trying to make. It's not something that should trivialize, but enhance.. And I don't think I'm able to express exactly what I'm trying to explain. It kind of goes along the lines of what I was saying in a different post though, about as a casual progress's and a RAider progress's, the % of difference should actually shrink somewhat, rather then stay at 50% (or whatever it is). I'll use HP/AC as a loose example of what I mean.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If 5 years ago, a Raiding warrior could achieve 8k Hp and 2k AC, unbuffed, and a Casual 5.5k hp and 1400 AC. Then 2 years ago, a Raiding Warrior could get 10k hp and 2500 AC, then a Casual might be able to get 7k HP and 2k AC. And at the beginning of next year a Warrior can get 15k HP and 3k AC unbuffed, a casual should be able to get 12k HP and 2300 AC, noticeably different, but not actually 50% worse of better, etc. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Using the current ideal, let's say 5 years from now, a casual warrior can obtain 20k HP and 6k AC unbuffed. Using the 50% rule, this would mean a RAiding Warrior could obtain 30k unbuffed and 9k AC... the gap gets huge as far as real number's are concerned. Let's say we do something like what I'm trying to say, and say a Raider should be only 20% better at that time. This would mean the Raider would now be at 24k hp and 7.2 AC. This would allow more group compatibility (for experience) and less trivial group content.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Everyone on both sides of this debate has great points, especially the Raider's viewpoint (Which has to be considered, they don't post to keep you or me down, but to try to be fair to all, including themselves). One thing that get's to me though, is when someone argue's about content not calling for this type of gear. Remember, we are trying to grind in the same content you call Trivial...&nbsp; Someone actually said a run through WOS to them, would be on par with me running through SoL B, it's that easy to them. This means the experience is that much easier for them to obtain, which is what is making it hard for Casuals to actually understand a Raider's point. If it's trivial for you, that means its' easy... Meaning easy to grind in, even solo where it would take a Casual a whole group, and possibly even longer to kill in. This was not the case 4 year's, or even 3 year's ago... This is where I believe CAsual player's are making the comparison with progression and gear. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Well, I hope at least some of what I am trying to express is understood, and not took the wrong way.</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							"One falsehood destroys a thousand truths." "Do not think of yourself higher than you ought to think" "If you are not guilty of the robbery then you should not hold on to the loot!" -NOEL BRYSON, Ph

The wise discuss ideas, the normal discuss events, the ignorant discuss other's.
							</div>
								
		</td></tr>
