		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
JazzyJoyce wrote:<BR>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If there was group-able content, that enable'd casual's to get drops that were compatible to top gear, then there should be GROUP Content, that demands this gear... 
<HR>
</DIV></BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>Then where does the seperation exist at all?&nbsp; Planning, mobilizing, and executing a raid force will always be more difficult and should thusly be more rewarding than ANY single group encounter.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>At the moment, GoD sewer trials, Riftseekers, MPG Trials, The Hive, Dreadspire... these are all very&nbsp;challenging single group encounters with very good rewards for casual players.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The game demands a lot from the raiders that need to execute with large numbers to a very high degree... so why shouldn't casuals be expected to take on the same thing in group encounters.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Anyone that complains that there isn't enough viable upgrade loot for casual players is really just being too lazy to form a good group and go get this stuff... I wouldn't expect a lazy guild that recruits poorly and doesn't have enough players online to break into Anguish any time soon... so why should casual single groupers be allowed the top gear of their playstyle for being just as poorly organized.</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=790661" target="_blank">
<img src="http://img219.echo.cx/img219/3240/darksig5zj.png" border="0" alt="" /> </a>
							</div>
								
